import Post from '../../layouts/Post.astro';
const meta = {
  title: 'How Do You Measure Whether a Language Is Compositional?',
  deck: 'When two neural agents invent a language to solve a game, is it compositional or a lookup table? Three metrics — topsim, posdis, bosdis — try to answer.',
  date: '2026-07-18',
  readtime: '8 min',
  project: 'Growing Meaning Spaces',
  tags: ['emergent-communication', 'compositionality', 'information-theory'],
};
const body = `
<p class="lead">Put two neural networks in a referential game — one sees an object and sends a
sequence of symbols, the other has to pick that object out of a lineup — and, given enough rounds,
they will invent a language. The uncomfortable question my BSc thesis kept circling is: <em>what
kind</em> of language? A compositional one, where symbols recombine to mean new things? Or a giant
brittle lookup table that happens to work on the training set and shatters the moment the world
grows? You cannot eyeball the answer. You have to measure it.</p>

<p>&ldquo;Growing meaning spaces&rdquo; is the experiment in the title: systematically enlarge the
space of things the agents must talk about — more attributes, more values per attribute — and watch
whether compositionality <em>emerges and holds</em> as the pressure to generalize increases.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 01</span> The game</span>Emergent communication in one paragraph</h2>
<p>A <strong>sender</strong> observes a structured input — an object encoded as attribute/value
pairs, say <em>(colour = blue, shape = triangle, size = large)</em> — and emits a discrete message
of length <span class="m">L</span> over a vocabulary of size <span class="m">V</span>. A
<strong>receiver</strong> reads the message and must identify the referent among distractors. Both
are trained end-to-end; because the channel is discrete, gradients come through REINFORCE or a
Gumbel-softmax relaxation. Nothing tells them <em>how</em> to encode meaning — a protocol simply
emerges from the pressure to be understood. The meaning space is the full grid of attribute/value
combinations, and &ldquo;growing&rdquo; it means adding attributes or values so that space expands
combinatorially.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 02</span> Topographic similarity</span>Do nearby meanings get nearby messages?</h2>
<p>The oldest and most intuitive metric. A language is compositional if <em>similar meanings map to
similar messages</em> — change one attribute, change a little of the message. Topographic similarity
(<strong>topsim</strong>) makes that precise: take every pair of objects, measure their distance in
meaning space (Hamming over attributes) and their distance in message space (edit distance over
symbols), and compute the rank correlation between the two lists of distances.</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span>Equation</span><span class="tag">Topographic similarity</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mrow>
          <mi>topsim</mi><mo>=</mo>
          <mi>&#961;</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo>
            <msub><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>meaning</mi></mrow></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>)</mo>
            <mo>,</mo>
            <msub><mi>d</mi><mrow><mi>message</mi></mrow></msub><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>)</mo>
          <mo>)</mo></mrow>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>EQ. 1 &mdash; Spearman ρ over all object pairs (i, j)</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>High topsim means the geometry of meaning survives the trip through the channel. It is a good
smell-test — but it is a single scalar over the whole language and can be fooled, which is why it
needs company.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 03</span> Disentanglement</span>Which symbol carries which attribute?</h2>
<p>Chaabouni et al. (2020) sharpened the question with two information-theoretic metrics that ask
where each attribute&rsquo;s information actually <em>lives</em> in the message.</p>

<p><strong>Positional disentanglement (posdis)</strong> asks whether each <em>position</em> in the
message is dedicated to a single attribute. For symbol position <span class="m">j</span>, rank the
attributes by mutual information with that symbol; the position is &ldquo;clean&rdquo; if the top
attribute dominates the second:</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span>Equation</span><span class="tag">Positional disentanglement</span></div>
    <div class="body">
      <math display="block" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
        <mrow>
          <mi>posdis</mi><mo>=</mo>
          <mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>L</mi></mfrac>
          <munderover><mo>&#8721;</mo><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>L</mi></munderover>
          <mfrac>
            <mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>;</mo><msubsup><mi>a</mi><mi>j</mi><mrow>(1)</mrow></msubsup><mo>)</mo>
              <mo>&#8722;</mo>
              <mi>I</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>;</mo><msubsup><mi>a</mi><mi>j</mi><mrow>(2)</mrow></msubsup><mo>)</mo></mrow>
            <mrow><mi>H</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>s</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo>)</mo></mrow>
          </mfrac>
        </mrow>
      </math>
    </div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>EQ. 2 &mdash; a<sup>(1)</sup>, a<sup>(2)</sup> are the top-two attributes by MI with symbol s<sub>j</sub></figcaption>
</figure>

<p><strong>Bag-of-symbols disentanglement (bosdis)</strong> asks the same question but throws away
order: it uses symbol <em>counts</em> rather than positions, rewarding languages where each symbol
in the vocabulary maps to a single attribute regardless of where it appears. Together the two catch
different compositional strategies — positional grammar versus an order-invariant &ldquo;bag&rdquo;
code — that topsim alone blurs into one number.</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 04</span> The experiment</span>What growing the space reveals</h2>
<p>With three lenses on compositionality, the thesis question becomes measurable: as the meaning
space grows, do topsim, posdis, and bosdis rise, and — crucially — do they <em>predict
generalization</em> to held-out attribute combinations the agents never saw in training? So I tracked
all three against generalization accuracy and against each other as the space expanded.</p>

<figure class="readout">
  <div class="screen">
    <div class="bar"><span class="tag">Experiments.ipynb</span><span>python</span></div>
    <div class="body"><pre><span class="c"># per run: sweep meaning-space size, log metrics + held-out accuracy</span>
<span class="k">for</span> size <span class="k">in</span> meaning_space_sizes:
    lang = train_referential_game(size, seeds=n_seeds)
    rows.append(dict(
        size=size,
        topsim=topographic_similarity(lang),
        posdis=positional_disentanglement(lang),
        bosdis=bag_of_symbols_disentanglement(lang),
        gen_acc=holdout_accuracy(lang),
    ))
<span class="c"># then: regress gen_acc ~ topsim + posdis + bosdis</span></pre></div>
  </div>
  <figcaption>the analysis is a metric sweep + a regression onto generalization</figcaption>
</figure>

<p>The recurring lesson of this literature — and of the plots that came out of these runs — is that
the three metrics do <em>not</em> move in lockstep. A language can score well on one and poorly on
another; a high topsim doesn&rsquo;t guarantee clean positional structure. Compositionality is not a
single axis, and the honest thing to report is a <em>profile</em> across metrics rather than one
headline number. The final arbiter is always the same: does the protocol generalize to combinations
it was never trained on?</p>

<h2><span class="sec"><span class="n">§ 05</span> Takeaways</span>What I&rsquo;d tell my earlier self</h2>
<ul class="clean">
  <li>Compositionality is multi-dimensional. Report topsim <em>and</em> a disentanglement metric —
    one scalar hides the failure modes of the other.</li>
  <li>Mutual-information metrics say <em>where</em> meaning lives in a message; correlational metrics
    say <em>whether</em> geometry is preserved. You want both.</li>
  <li>Generalization to unseen combinations is the ground truth. A metric is only useful insofar as
    it predicts it.</li>
  <li>Growing the meaning space is the right stress test: compositional structure is exactly what
    should pay off as the world gets bigger.</li>
</ul>

<p class="endnote">From my BSc thesis, <em>Growing Meaning Spaces</em>. Metric definitions follow
Brighton &amp; Kirby (topsim) and Chaabouni et al., 2020 (posdis / bosdis).</p>
`;
